    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "e5de285b_e2488bb2",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 133,
      "author": {
        "id": 5255
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-02T17:42:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "SkSampledCodec is how we create scaled down versions of images. It does a more complex version of the following:\n\n  codec-\u003estartIncrementalDecode(...);\n  auto* sampler \u003d codec-\u003egetSampler(true);\n  sampler-\u003esetSampleX(sampleX);\n  sampler-\u003esetSampleY(sampleY);\n  codec-\u003eincrementalDecode(\u0026rowsDecoded);\n\nIt actually has two ways of doing it - scanline decoding came first, and I think it\u0027s more straightforward. But it was incompatible with libpng\u0027s incremental decoding, so I came up with incrementalDecode to support both true incremental decoding and this sampled decode.\n\nPart of the goal of the sampled decode is to avoid allocating the buffer for the full sized image. But Wuffs allocates the full sized image anyway. So maybe we shouldn\u0027t even use SkSampledCodec. Instead, we could have another adapter like SkWebpAdapterCodec. It would decode each frame, and if the client wants a scale we can just use the drawing engine to draw the image with a scale.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 133,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 133,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "8a250dc152e4a93801f77cbcb19c2e490656b67b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d00e5a07_7d0bb344",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 133,
      "author": {
        "id": 8223
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-04T01:23:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "There\u0027s some tension (see comments below) between needing the sampler to exist *before* incrementalDecode is called, but the frame rect is really only knowable *after* incrementalDecode is called.\n\nPerhaps getSampler could return a dummy sampler, something that you can call setSample{X,Y} on and save that argument somewhere, but the real sampler (made by SkSwizzler::Make) only gets made in onIncrementalDecode, after the frame rect is known. Immediately after the real sampler is made, the previous setSample{X,Y} args are forwarded on from the dummy sampler to the real one.\n\nOr... if you want to skip SkSampledCodec and use something similar to SkWebpAdapterCodec, that sounds workable too, although I haven\u0027t really studied SkWebpAdapterCodec. That might be a better long term approach anyway, if Wuffs will eventually (I can re-prioritize so that s/eventually/soon/, if necessary??) be able to do its own sampling.",
      "parentUuid": "e5de285b_e2488bb2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 133,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 133,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "8a250dc152e4a93801f77cbcb19c2e490656b67b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "bd619ff7_34707b33",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 133,
      "author": {
        "id": 5255
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-05T20:12:59Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e There\u0027s some tension (see comments below) between needing the sampler to exist *before* incrementalDecode is called, but the frame rect is really only knowable *after* incrementalDecode is called.\n\nRight. That\u0027s part of why I moved decodeFrameConfig into onStartIncrementalDecode.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e Perhaps getSampler could return a dummy sampler, something that you can call setSample{X,Y} on and save that argument somewhere, but the real sampler (made by SkSwizzler::Make) only gets made in onIncrementalDecode, after the frame rect is known. Immediately after the real sampler is made, the previous setSample{X,Y} args are forwarded on from the dummy sampler to the real one.\n\nThat seems a little extra tricky to me.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e Or... if you want to skip SkSampledCodec and use something similar to SkWebpAdapterCodec, that sounds workable too, although I haven\u0027t really studied SkWebpAdapterCodec. That might be a better long term approach anyway, if Wuffs will eventually (I can re-prioritize so that s/eventually/soon/, if necessary??) be able to do its own sampling.\n\nSkWebpAdapterCodec doesn\u0027t do anything particularly interesting. It just forwards its arguments to SkWebpCodec. Wuffs will be a little more complex (at least to start with), since it needs to handle the scaling/subsetting.\n\nAs for priorities, if we\u0027re going in this direction (SkWuffsAdapterCodec), then I\u0027m fine with landing your CL to use the swizzler with just the change to use the right colors per device. There\u0027s still a bug related to animations with partial frame updates, but that is not new to using the swizzler (I think). We will need to write SkWuffsAdapterCodec in order to switch Android, but AFAIK flutter doesn\u0027t currently use subsetting/sampling.",
      "parentUuid": "d00e5a07_7d0bb344",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 133,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 133,
        "endChar": 69
      },
      "revId": "8a250dc152e4a93801f77cbcb19c2e490656b67b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "6c395aa9_34567f54",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 333,
      "author": {
        "id": 5255
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-02T17:42:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I moved this here so that fFrameConfig\u0027s bounds will be set when SkSampledCodec calls getSampler in between this and onIncrementalDecode (which is where we create the swizzler with knowledge of the frame rect).",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 325,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 333,
        "endChar": 5
      },
      "revId": "8a250dc152e4a93801f77cbcb19c2e490656b67b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7473564c_79396121",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 333,
      "author": {
        "id": 8223
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-04T01:23:42Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hmm... but what if the input stream is paused (e.g. reading over the network) somewhere where we can\u0027t completely decode the fFrameConfig? This is the \"if (status \u003d\u003d wuffs_base__suspension__short_read) { return SkCodec::kIncompleteInput; }\" case you\u0027ve added a few lines above.\n\nEven if, later on, the input stream has more data, nobody calls oSID aka onStartIncrementalDecode (and therefore this-\u003edecodeFrameConfig) again. oSID is only called once, oID aka onIncrementalDecode is the one that can be called multiple times, right?\n\nA different approach is to get the frame rectangle from fFrames instead of (re-)parsing via this-\u003edecodeFrameConfig. But that assumes that onGetFrameCount has been called (which updates fFrames as a side effect). Can we make that assumption?",
      "parentUuid": "6c395aa9_34567f54",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 325,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 333,
        "endChar": 5
      },
      "revId": "8a250dc152e4a93801f77cbcb19c2e490656b67b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "0dcdc587_b9b2d66d",
        "filename": "src/codec/SkWuffsCodec.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 333,
      "author": {
        "id": 5255
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-11-05T20:12:59Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Hmm... but what if the input stream is paused (e.g. reading over the network) somewhere where we can\u0027t completely decode the fFrameConfig? This is the \"if (status \u003d\u003d wuffs_base__suspension__short_read) { return SkCodec::kIncompleteInput; }\" case you\u0027ve added a few lines above.\n\u003e \n\u003e Even if, later on, the input stream has more data, nobody calls oSID aka onStartIncrementalDecode (and therefore this-\u003edecodeFrameConfig) again. oSID is only called once, oID aka onIncrementalDecode is the one that can be called multiple times, right?\n\nDid I say that? If so, then my mistake. oSID can be called multiple times if it returns kIncompleteInput.\n\n\u003e \n\u003e A different approach is to get the frame rectangle from fFrames instead of (re-)parsing via this-\u003edecodeFrameConfig. But that assumes that onGetFrameCount has been called (which updates fFrames as a side effect). Can we make that assumption?\n\nI considered that, too. Currently, Chromium will always call onGetFrameCount first, and so does Android. But I like the idea that it\u0027s not required.",
      "parentUuid": "7473564c_79396121",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 325,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 333,
        "endChar": 5
      },
      "revId": "8a250dc152e4a93801f77cbcb19c2e490656b67b",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
